article.description:
Antawn Jamison started strong and never
slowed down.
article.headline: Golden State still trail Suns by four in race for playoffs
article.linkText: Jamison goes for 41 as Warriors stay in chase
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Antawn Jamison started strong and never slowed down.
Antawn Jamison
Forward
Golden State Warriors
Profile
2002-2003 SEASON STATISTICS
GM PPG RPG APG FG% FT%
76 22.0 6.9 1.8 .466 .794
Jamison scored a season-high 41 points on 17-for-24 shooting and grabbed 14 rebounds as the Warriors snapped a three-game losing streak with a 106-99 victory over the Denver Nuggets on Sunday. ''I struggled the last two games so I wanted to be more aggressive,'' said Jamison, who has 17 games of 30 or more points this season. ''Once I got it going, my teammates did a great job of getting me the ball in my sweet spots.'' Troy Murphy added 14 points as the Warriors (37-40) remained four games back of the eighth-place Phoenix Suns in the Western Conference with five games remaining. ''When you have a guy going like that, you have to get him the ball and let him score,'' said Warriors guard Jason Richardson, who added 11 points and six assists. The Warriors have won 16 more games than they did last year and will finish the season with their highest victory total since the 1993-94 team won 50 games. ''They have several players that can get 40 on a given night,'' said Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik. ''One of them showed that tonight. He was just outstanding. He is a great offensive player.'' Juwan Howard scored 24 points for the Nuggets, who lost their seventh in a row on the road and third consecutive overall. Shammond Williams added 14 points. ''Jamison broke our backs,'' said Howard. ''He had a monster game and we allowed him to get into a comfortable rhythm.'' The Warriors won all four games against Denver this season, their first series sweep over the Nuggets since 1991-92. Denver, on pace to become the second-lowest scoring team (83.6 entering play Sunday) in NBA history, has scored 100 or more points just five times this season. The Nuggets are 4-35 on the road this season. The Warriors led by as many as 17 in the third quarter, but Denver went on an 11-4 run in the final four minutes and drew to 80-70 entering the final quarter. The Nuggets cut the lead to 93-86 with 3:54 left on Howard's layup. Adonal Foyle blocked Rodney White's shot 30 seconds later, and the Warriors went on to regain a double-digit advantage. Jamison, who recorded his 16th double-double, scored 24 points in the first half -- 17 in the first quarter -- while making 10 of 11 shots. ''He's not a guy you have to call his number a lot,'' said Warriors' coach Eric Musselman. ''We'll try to get him some shots but he gets a lot of stuff in the flow of the game.'' Game notes
Warriors forward Danny Fortson, who's appeared in just 17 games this year, missed the game because of the flu. ... Nuggets guard Devin Brown, signed to a 10-day contract Friday, was in uniform for the first time. ... The Warriors scored 30 or more in the first quarter for the fourth time in five games. ... Denver forward Ryan Bowen missed his ninth game with a sternum and abdominal bruise. ... Warriors forward Chris Mills has missed the past 14 games with left Achilles tendinitis. ... The Nuggets averaged 92.2 points a game last year. ... The 1998-99 Chicago Bulls averaged 81.9 points a game.
